In addition to other interesting features, CQDs are particularly well-known for their photoluminescence (PL) from a fundamental and application-oriented perspective. In the majority of early studies, one distinguishing feature of CQD-PL was the interaction between wavelength and intensity(Kwon et al., 2015). CQD surfaces have different nanoparticle sizes (quantum effect) and/or different emissive traps than their surfaces, but scientists cannot determine for sure whether those factors are responsible or another cause. (Section 3.2). Nonetheless, an increasing number of examples have been discovered with an λex independent emission position, which could be ascribed to their homogenous size and surface composition(
                        Zhao et al., 2008; Wang et al., 2013b
                        ).

To be more precise, the up-converted photoluminescence of CQDs, caused by an optical phenomenon in which a material produces shorter wavelength light than the solar excitation source, imparts it the ability to scatter sunlight into visible and near-infrared regions (Table 2
                        ). Additionally, photoinduced CQDs are exceptional electron donors and acceptors, leading to the effective electron-hole separation. Consequently, CQDs can assist as an adaptable constituent in photocatalyst designs, such as, (i) electron mediator, (ii) photosensitizer, (iii) spectral converter, (iv) sole photocatalyst, (v) photocenter and (vi) catalytic center (Li et al., 2010a). In several instances, these various effects have been observed to be instantaneous. Fig. 8
                         explain the multifaceted functions of CQDs and the cooperative photocatalytic reaction mechanisms of CQDs.


   Electrochemical Biosensing using CQDs
 Electrochemical biosensing is frequently performed with CQDs due to their excellent electron transport capabilities. Also, CQDs could interact directly with target analytes in order to alter the electrochemical signals of electrodes. For this reason, CQDs are typically directly loaded onto an electrode surface in an electrochemical biosensor, and the modifications to signals (current) that occur as a result of their interactions with biomolecules are collected for detection and analysis of the target analytes. In a study, Jing et al. created an electrochemical biosensor for the detection of dopamine directly from doped CDs, without requiring chemical solvents or catalysts for its synthesis (Jiang et al., 2015). In addition to their surface carboxyl groups, CDs contain an abundance of dopamine-interacting electrostatic groups. The current of an electrode will shift when it comes into contact with dopamine when an electrode loaded with CDs is in contact with it. The dopamine concentration is linearly correlated with the current change. Through this sensor, able to rapidly sense the level of dopamine in human serum and urine, attaining a linear range of 5 × 10−8 to 8 × 10−6 mol/L and a detection limit of 1.2 × 10−9 mol/L (Huang et al., 2015) (Table 3
).
